{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659915","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659915"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:17:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:17:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21091"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21091"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115461"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13966"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97464"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"385"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"1449"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39809"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115461"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of altered bowel habits, intermittent rectal bleeding, and unintentional weight loss of 5 kg. He has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His regular medications include perindopril and atorvastatin. His father died of colorectal cancer at age 70. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild tenderness in the left lower quadrant without palpable masses. Digital rectal examination shows no abnormalities. Faecal occult blood test is positive. Colonoscopy reveals a 4 cm mass in the sigmoid colon, and biopsies confirm adenocarcinoma. The patient undergoes a sigmoid colectomy with regional lymphadenectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely gross pathological appearance of the resected specimen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A flat, depressed lesion with central ulceration","An ulcerated, fungating mass extending through the bowel wall","A smooth, pedunculated polyp with intact mucosa","Multiple small nodules scattered throughout the mucosa","A diffuse thickening of the bowel wall with a leather-bottle appearance"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic symptoms of colorectal cancer including altered bowel habits, rectal bleeding, and weight loss. The gross pathological appearance of the resected specimen is important for staging and prognosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAn ulcerated, fungating mass extending through the bowel wall\u003C/strong\u003E is the most typical gross appearance of colon adenocarcinoma. These tumours commonly present as exophytic, ulcerated masses that grow into the lumen and invade through the layers of the bowel wall. The cut surface often appears white-grey and firm with areas of necrosis. Here is a typical example (Image 1). This appearance correlates with the patient\u0027s presentation of a symptomatic mass that was large enough (4 cm) to cause bleeding and changes in bowel habits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA smooth, pedunculated polyp with intact mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E typically represents a benign adenomatous polyp or early adenocarcinoma arising within a polyp (malignant polyp). Here is an example (Image 2). While adenocarcinomas can arise from adenomatous polyps, once they become invasive cancers, they usually lose the smooth, pedunculated appearance and develop ulceration and invasion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA flat, depressed lesion with central ulceration\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen in some early colorectal cancers, particularly those developing through the serrated neoplasia pathway. Here is an example (Image 3). However, this appearance is less common for a symptomatic 4 cm sigmoid mass that has been present long enough to cause weight loss and altered bowel habits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA diffuse thickening of the bowel wall with a leather-bottle appearance\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of diffuse-type gastric carcinoma (linitis plastica) rather than colon adenocarcinoma. This appearance is rare in colorectal cancer and would be an unusual finding in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple small nodules scattered throughout the mucosa\u003C/strong\u003E would be more consistent with conditions such as lymphoma, carcinoid tumors, or metastatic disease to the colon rather than primary colon adenocarcinoma, which typically presents as a solitary mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gross pathological appearance of colon adenocarcinoma is important for determining the extent of local invasion (T stage). The depth of invasion through the bowel wall, along with lymph node involvement (N stage) and the presence of distant metastases (M stage), forms the basis of the TNM staging system, which guides treatment decisions and provides prognostic information.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Colon adenocarcinoma typically presents as an ulcerated, fungating mass that may extend through the bowel wall.","Gross pathological features of colon adenocarcinoma include ulceration, raised irregular borders, and invasion through the bowel wall.","Pathological staging of colon cancer is determined by depth of invasion, lymph node involvement, and presence of distant metastases."],"references":["Uthman, Ed. Colon Adenocarcinoma (gross) NZ7_1386. Flikr. Accessed under license CC By 2.0: https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/2.0/deed.en. Accessed at: https://www.flickr.com/photos/euthman/51440373932/in/pool-labmed/","Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020; Chapter 17; pages 813-817."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97464"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21091"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21833"},{"type":"media","id":"21835"},{"type":"media","id":"21836"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21833"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2Zg4FwKf9PcrKDmZNpOP9bbYHr7GBq.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2Zg4FwKf9PcrKDmZNpOP9bbYHr7GBq.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"21835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21835"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1nUBik8EE4aUE1G5WYpBOAoHWw1xJa.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1nUBik8EE4aUE1G5WYpBOAoHWw1xJa.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":368}},{"type":"media","id":"21836","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21836"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rS32YUx54nXSPWmPmBswDS6H7PHKfI.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rS32YUx54nXSPWmPmBswDS6H7PHKfI.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97